  <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> Cadence exhibits remarkably stable, world-class margins. Software margins are fundamentally structurally high. Any short-term dips in FCF margin are often timing differences in tax payments or temporary shifts in working capital, not structural deterioration.</p>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100)}% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate and growth. High-growth software companies have the bulk of their value in the terminal value, making the discount rate the biggest driver of the final number.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Accelerated AI Chip Design:</strong> If hyperscalers (Google, Amazon, Meta) significantly increase custom silicon designs, Cadence's IP and verification revenue could far exceed our 15% growth estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>System Design Analytics expansion:</strong> Expansion beyond core EDA into broader systems analysis (aerospace, automotive) unlocks massively larger total addressable markets.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing power leverage:</strong> Because EDA tools are a rounding error relative to the cost of a ruined tape-out, Cadence can push pricing significantly higher without losing customers.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical restrictions:</strong> Strict US export controls on advanced semiconductor tech to China heavily restrict a significant historical revenue base for Cadence.</li>
    <li><strong>Semiconductor downcycles:</strong> While somewhat insulated by subscription models, a prolonged severe downturn in global semiconductor R&D budgets will compress growth below 15%.</li>
    <li><strong>Synopsys dominance:</strong> Their primary rival, Synopsys (SNPS), could win critical standard-setting battles in next-gen AI-driven EDA tools.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple for Cadence?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Cadence frequently trades at P/E multiples above 60x or 70x. Multiple-based valuation struggles to justify these prices without pure extrapolation. A DCF grounds the valuation in the actual cash generated, forcing us to ask: "Does the math justify the multiple?" Usually, for wide-moat software, it justifies a very high but mathematically bound value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the discount rate 9.5%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate is the required return. With the 10-year Treasury at 4.18% and CDNS having a beta around 1.1, the CAPM model suggests a cost of equity just over 9%. We round to 9.5% to maintain a sufficient margin of safety against execution risks.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 15% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">EDA tools are the bedrock of the AI hardware revolution. You cannot build a modern Nvidia, AMD, or custom hyperscaler chip without Cadence or Synopsys. That systemic importance drives massive, high-margin software license growth.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

